##Someone who took an oath

Estimated reading time: 13 minutes

Author | Zhongqingbao Zhongqingwang Xinxin, Sun Qingling, Lei Yu

For the past two months, the white robes have been Wuhan's most reassuring garb, with those wearing them receiving the highest courtesies and the most pressure.

When Zhu Liangwen, deputy director of the Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Fudan University, flew from Shanghai to Wuhan with a 130-person medical team, the vast Tianhe Airport was lit up for just one flight, a "treatment" he had never seen.

On January 23, in an effort to stop the spread of the new coronavirus, Wuhan closed its doors, allowing only a small number of people to pass on official duties related to the "epidemic" of war. Then, including New Year's Eve, more than 35,000 doctors and nurses from all over China made their way to Wuhan by various means of transport, about a third of them young people born in the 1990s and 2000s. More than one person has quoted as saying: In 2003 SARS epidemic, he was just a protected child, now it's his turn to protect others.

Speaking of these people, Ding Xiangyang, Deputy secretary-general of the State Council and a member of the Central Committee's Steering Group to Hubei, said, "the children in the eyes of their parents yesterday have become the backbone of the new era of the Republic and become the pride and hope of our country. "

In Wuhan, you can find many such young people whose stories are already part of the city's memory: A first-line doctor at the same local hospital weaned a seven-month-old; another doctor, she left her two children with relatives and went to the front line with her husband, who is also a doctor; another doctor in his 20s went to the head of the department and said that the children were still young and that she was afraid and wanted to resign. In fact, instead of leaving, instead in their own symptoms, still said that as long as rule out infection, but also "back. ".

A doctor named Gan Ruyi had just returned to his hometown in Jingzhou, more than 300 kilometers away, to prepare for the new year, before the city was closed. She decided to return to Wuhan after she learned of the "closure of the city" .

There is no public transportation to choose from. The 24-year-old cycled, hitchhiked and walked all the way back to his post in four days and three nights -- to the Fanghu branch of the Jinkou Health Centre in the Summer District of Wuhan. A temporary pass issued to her by the local government listed "bicycle" on the license plate.

Her wheels are turning towards a plague rarely seen in human history.

"The hardest scales" were given to Wuhan

On the night of Feb. 7, Zhu led a 130-person medical team into downtown Wuhan. They saw that all the shops were closed, and there were no cars or pedestrians on the streets. Passing the city's landmarks, the Yangtze River Bridge and the Yellow Crane Tower River, the team's vivacious young men did not react with the surprise and Glee of Fresh Off the Boat, and all were silent. "An indescribable feeling, " Zhu said.

An animation was created depicting medical workers from all over the country riding to Wuhan's aid: flags were lit up across China after the city issued a "call for help. ". Famous hospitals around have sent medical teams, Xiehe, Xiangya, Qilu, Hwaseo... Some people described: "The village of the dragon are the hardest scale to Wuhan. "

"there is probably no precedent in human history for such a large-scale gathering of medical forces, " said Dong Jiahong, executive vice president of the Chinese Medical Doctor Association and a member of the Chinese Academy of Engineering.

Beijing's Tsinghua Changgeng Hospital, where Dong works, sent more than 20 people to support Wuhan. When informed, a doctor did not even have time to return home, straight to the airport, his family sent his luggage to the airport.

Wang Rui, head nurse in the Department of gastroenterology at Hwaseo Hospital in Sichuan University, was sent to Wuhan with the medical team on Feb. 7, a week before her husband, Chen Xinzu, was sent there. The couple did not see each other for more than a week at the east side of Wuhan University People's Hospital on the right bank of the Yangtze River and the Wuhan Union Hospital on the Left Bank.

As the story of a husband and wife on the same page continued to be dug up by reporters, there was some concern and even consideration of whether to forcibly remove one of them, in order to prevent the extreme situation may cause irreparable damage to the family of the health care workers.

"One more day. " Seven, eight days

Many medical staff at Wuhan Red Cross Hospital cried when they saw the Sichuan medical team members coming to support them. "The reinforcements have finally arrived. ".

In the days leading up to the Spring Festival, the hospital, just a kilometer from the south China Seafood Market, was on the verge of collapse. The smoking section was quickly filled, and then the physical examination section was transformed into the breathing section, and then the oncology section... until the hospital became an infectious disease hospital.

On January 21, the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital was designated as a designated hospital for the treatment of new crown pneumonia patients. The number of outpatients on January 22 was 1,700. The number of outpatients on January 23 reached a peak of 2,400.

"We usually have 800 to 1,000 outpatient visits, " said Xiong Nian, director of the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital. As a result of the limited number of early sentinel hospitals, even 20 km away from patients have run to the Red Cross Hospital.

At the time, the city was in crisis.

Wuhan used to have only two infectious disease hospitals with no more than 1,000 beds. But at the height of the epidemic, more than 3,000 new beds were needed each day. "It's a challenge for any city in the world, " Ding said at a news conference in March.

The huge gap between supply and demand revealed by the data is a specific and minor challenge for medical staff at the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital.

Surgery, gynecology, pediatrics, facial features... all departments of the medical staff are dealing with the same virus, or not enough people, all the department heads are looking for hospital leaders to send reinforcements.

"hold on one more day. " In the same words, a hospital leader to the department directors "have said seven or eight days, " "where do I have people? "

Nurse's salary went up to $30,000 a month, and no one showed up. The nurse doubles as a nurse and is responsible for the day-to-day care of the critically ill.

The doctors and nurses in this hospital have been severely cut down because the protective equipment can not keep up. "infected a batch, down a batch. " Xiong Nian said, even the head of the nursing department also on the line, eventually infected with the virus.

Leibo County, a member of the Sichuan medical team, went to the pharmacy to look for medicine and found that no one was there. The pharmacists were either "caught" or had gone to the clinic to help.

The husband of a hospital staff member has been in hospital for a month with new pneumonia and she has no time to visit him. When the medic asked about her husband, she began to cry. "I couldn't care less about him. "

Some return to the fold, some never return to the fold

To This Day, Wuhan Red Cross Hospital is still filled with tension. Red and yellow "water horses" guard the Downtown Hospital, while staff wearing protective clothing scan warily anyone who tries to approach the hospital.

"The whole hospital is a polluted area, " Xiong said. His duty colleague took the visitor's temperature, keeping an eye out for viruses that might break in at any moment. But he seemed so calm. The 80-year-old head of the hospital led the team through the most difficult time, and now with more than 300 Sichuan medical team medical staff, continue to treat patients.

When the early patients flooded into the hospital, there was no protective clothing. He wore a mask and an isolation suit to shuttle around the outpatient area and dispatch the limited medical care. The most deadly is the shortage of protective materials, he begged people to borrow protective clothing.

More than 3,000 health care workers in Hubei Province were infected in the early days of the outbreak, 40 percent of them in hospitals. The most dramatic deaths were those of Dr Peng Yinhua, 29, and Dr Shays, 29... four doctors have been killed at Wuhan Central Hospital and the head of Wuchang Hospital, Liu Zhiming, has been killed. For these people, Wuhan people do not know how many tears.

Some medical staff return to the workforce after recovery -- as if to say they have just wandered off to a more normal place.

Janne, a 24-year-old nurse in the Emergency Department of Wuhan University People's Hospital, was diagnosed on New Year's Eve. After her recovery, she was back on the team. About 10 days after her recovery, she went to the hospital and donated 300 ml of serum in the hope that her antibodies would help others.

"It's like pulling death from the hands of the living in the dark, fighting for their lives, " she said. "If I don't go, I'll regret it for the rest of my life. "

The experience of going from nurse to patient to nurse and back against the new coronavirus made Janne feel more aware of the patient's eyes. "The despair and the fear, I know as well as they do. "

Patients see the world differently than people do, she says. They don't just need treatment and care, they need to be encouraged. "What is more important than being alive is hope. "

Usually blood donors have to do "apportion" people, impressive

With a group of young nurses to Wuhan, Ruijin Hospital Operating Room head nurse Wang Xiaoning originally did not know, thought they will cry nose, make mood.

More than half of Ruijin's 130-strong medical team are post-90s. The father and mother of nurse Zhu Youqi once felt, go up Wuhan a line such big event, still do not turn oneself daughter. Zhu Youqi wants to clarify his image in front of his parents: "In the department, we are the mainstay after 90. "

After working in Wuhan for a while, Wang Xiaoning had to admit that the children's ideas and enthusiasm were "out of our reach" .

Because it's difficult to communicate while wearing a protective suit, nurses write common questions on the suit and point to the patient without using words. Several "soul painters" also drew their favorite patterns on protective clothing, "Crayon small new" and other cartoon characters shuttle back and forth, regulating the atmosphere of the ward.

Within 10 minutes of the announcement, more than 130 of the 153 nurses in the operating room had signed up. Wang Xiaoning to this group of"usually give blood to want to make"apportion"young person is impressed.

Born in 1990, anesthesiologist enjoyed working as a team: a nurse with a syringe and a look in the doctor's eyes told her when to push; a patient's mouth opened without an anesthesiologist speaking, the laryngoscope and tube are handed over, and the guide core is removed as the tube slips over the epiglottis.

The intubator is described as a "death squad" , the moment the patient's airway is opened, they are closest to the virus. But Miao described the intubation as a "plane crash landing" : Not by the captain alone, but by the entire team.

As they descend from the battlefield, young doctors and nurses are occasionally reminded of the "nightmare" of spot checks and professional exams.

Wang Lei, a nurse, said that scenes that "make people's hair stand on end, " usually feel useless, to Wuhan felt too important, "battlefield" performance, rely on the accumulation of ordinary.

The young doctor and the old oath

On January 14, on her way home from her night shift at the Caidian District People's Hospital in Wuhan, she learned that a patient with a high degree of suspected new pneumonia had been admitted to the unit and returned to the hospital. She was infected, and she died in the line of duty.

His son was just over two years old and didn't know his mother was gone. When asked, his father replied, "mom is at work. ".

When the news broke, her former college teacher and fellow students felt sorry for her -- she was "doctor material, " from a medical family, and showed interest in practicing medicine as a freshman. Class Monitor Rao Yan said that about half of the students did a doctor, but also a career change, Shaisi on the doctor of the profession of strong feelings, impressive.

She recalls how, more than five years ago, her colleague, Ying Ke Tsai, described the Hippocratic Oath as a must read for any medical student -- a foretaste of what many would later become.

She recalled the details of Shays to reporters as a patient and gentle doctor, a patient who was scared and responsive to treatment, and a respected colleague.

Cai Yingke said, sometimes, the sacred feeling of occupation is to need to experience some things to feel, this time, sacrifice is around.

"You've read the Hippocratic Oath, and it's your job to stand up for yourself, " she said, feeling that the oath had been worshipped before, and now she knew that it was a step-by-step process.

Saving a patient is like putting a fish back in the water

Miao Shenghao decided to go to Wuhan because he didn't want to regret his career.

The anesthesiologist was born into a family of doctors: Her aunt was a cardiologist, her sister, a radiologist, was married to an oral surgeon, and her aunt and cousin were also doctors.

Because the doctor is always on duty, it is difficult for the whole family to get together every Spring Festival. But he couldn't remember what the elders had complained about.

He enjoyed the sense of accomplishment of being a doctor, especially "when you get it right. ". Every time he finished the intubation and watched the patient's Oxygenation rise, he felt "like putting a fish back in the water. " .

The answer to career choice is mixed. Yao Mengyi, a nurse who was born in 1996, was inspired by the scene of a hat-giving ceremony in a TV series, It Started With a Kiss, when she was a child.

Before arriving in Wuhan, Yao Mengyi, a nurse in the emergency room, had been treated for suspected new pneumonia. Wearing protective clothing for the first time, she felt "too scared. ". But when the application notice came down, she immediately made an appointment with a friend to go to Wuhan.

Dr. Dewey, a suction physician, grew up curious about the handwritten medical books he left behind, and his family wanted him to carry on the family tradition. But the post-90s joked that practicing medicine might have something to do with his "horoscope" and "an interest in mysteries" .

When Dewey joined the company in 2019, he was prepared to face respiratory disease at any time. The outbreak forced him to call off the wedding, and he went to his father-in-law's house for a "quick walk. ". Then he went to Wuhan.

It's a job that's always needed

In this war "epidemic" , Zhu Zhuzhuzhuzhuzhuowen saw the mature side of young people. "They are very good, some of them are very young, " he said of his college classmates. "The youngest job is only two and a half years old. But I think this team is very trustworthy. "

Despite the challenges and difficulties faced by the medical profession, Zhu was more willing to speak to the younger generation about the value of medicine. "It's a job that's always needed. "

Although extreme cases of doctor-patient relationships occur from time to time, they are not mainstream and "should not be, " he said.

Although Chinese doctors live in a less-than-ideal social ecology, they remain "New Heart, " said Dong Jiahong, an academician at the University of Hong Kong, "The majority of medical staff to maintain the basic professional quality, that is, can not ignore death, this is also their mission. ".

He has decided to give more subsidies to the hospital's front-line medical staff than the state-mandated level of subsidies.

He expects that after this outbreak, the country and society will be able to understand and respect doctors and care for doctors, not only in the special period of fighting the epidemic.

"The world appreciates your efforts to find the best treatment and prevent the spread of the virus, " who director-general Tan Desai also paid tribute to Chinese medical staff on social media.

Zhong Nanshan's doctor, who became known to the public during the SARS epidemic in 2003, is now in his 80s. After SARS, he has a big regret: the public, government departments and the media "some of the prejudice against the medical profession has not changed. ".

He once lamented that doctors could not change from "angels in White" to "wolves in white" once SARS had gone and the Wenchuan County earthquake had passed.

This time, he said in an interview: "I must reiterate once again that the vast majority of our medical personnel have never left the name of the angel in White. " He stressed that it was evident from the performance at different times, "We never change. ".

Zhu Zhuzhuzhuowen told reporters that the young generation of medical staff is not a blank sheet of paper, but "a high starting point" on the start of life.

He has decided to wait until the next time to Wuhan, do not want to be treated with special treatment of the medical team, only hope to be an ordinary tourist. In this regard, he agrees with many young people -- many of whom have already expressed their collective yearning for Wuhan snacks on social networking sites -- that it is their "hometown of hot and dry noodles" .
